WEBVTT

00:22.780 --> 00:25.580
CHAPTER IV.

00:25.580 --> 00:28.060
Jonathan Harker's Journal Continued

01:47.020 --> 01:48.800
18th of May

02:16.140 --> 02:17.960
19th of May

03:58.280 --> 03:59.320
19th of May

04:10.820 --> 04:16.040
There is a chance of escape, or at any rate of being able to send word home.

04:16.780 --> 04:20.560
A band of Sagani have come to the castle and are encamped in the courtyard.

04:21.200 --> 04:25.160
These are gypsies. I have notes of them in my book.

04:26.140 --> 04:30.600
They are peculiar to this part of the world, though allied to the ordinary gypsies all the

04:30.600 --> 04:37.300
world over. There are thousands of them in Hungary and Transylvania who are almost outside all law.

04:38.400 --> 04:44.240
They attach themselves as a rule to some great noble or boyar and call themselves by his name.

04:45.040 --> 04:48.920
They are fearless and without religion, save superstition,

04:49.300 --> 04:52.420
and they talk only their own varieties of the Romani tongue.

04:53.980 --> 04:57.700
I shall write some letters home and shall try to get them to have them posted.

04:58.440 --> 05:01.680
I have already spoken to them through my window to begin acquaintanceship.

05:02.500 --> 05:06.300
They took their hats off and made obeisance and many signs,

05:06.680 --> 05:10.660
which however I could not understand any more than I could their spoken language.

05:12.900 --> 05:20.040
I have written the letters. Minas is in shorthand and I simply ask Mr. Hawkins to communicate with

05:20.040 --> 05:26.180
her. To her I have explained my situation, but without the horrors which I may only surmise.

05:27.300 --> 05:31.840
It would shock and frighten her to death were I to expose my heart to her.

05:32.920 --> 05:38.660
Should the letters not carry, then the Count shall not yet know my secret or the extent of my

05:38.660 --> 05:46.160
knowledge. I have given the letters. I threw them through the bars of my window with a gold

05:46.160 --> 05:51.240
piece and made what signs I could to have them posted. The man who took them pressed them to his

05:51.240 --> 05:58.420
heart and bowed and then put them in his cap. I could do no more. I stole back to the study

05:58.420 --> 06:03.460
and began to read. As the Count did not come in, I have written here,

06:04.900 --> 06:11.520
The Count has come. He sat down beside me and said in his smoothest voice as he opened two letters,

06:12.560 --> 06:19.380
The Sagani has given me these, of which though I know not whence they come, I shall of course

06:19.380 --> 06:27.700
take care. See, he must have looked at it. One is from you and to my friend Peter Hawkins.

06:28.540 --> 06:32.860
The other, here he caught sight of the strange symbols as he opened the envelope,

06:33.460 --> 06:37.540
and the dark look came into his face and his eyes blazed wickedly.

06:38.920 --> 06:46.840
The other is a vile thing, an outrage upon friendship and hospitality. It is not signed.

06:48.420 --> 06:54.540
Well, so it cannot matter to us. And he calmly held letter and envelope

06:54.540 --> 06:57.660
in the flame of the lamp till they were consumed.

06:58.860 --> 07:06.420
Then he went on. The letter to Hawkins that I shall, of course, send on since it is yours.

07:07.440 --> 07:14.120
Your letters are sacred to me. Your pardon, my friend, that unknowingly I did break the seal.

07:14.860 --> 07:21.780
Will you not cover it again? He held out the letter to me and with a courteous bow handed me

07:21.780 --> 07:27.300
a clean envelope. I could only redirect it and hand it to him in silence.

07:27.920 --> 07:31.300
When he went out of the room I could hear the key turn softly.

07:32.300 --> 07:35.740
A minute later I went over and tried it, and the door was locked.

07:37.520 --> 07:41.440
When, an hour or two after, the Count came quietly into the room,

07:41.920 --> 07:47.580
his coming awakened me, for I had gone to sleep on the sofa. He was very courteous and very

07:47.580 --> 07:51.040
cheery in his manner, and seeing that I had been sleeping he said,

07:51.600 --> 07:57.980
So, my friend, you are tired. Get to bed. There is the surest rest.

07:59.200 --> 08:04.380
I may not have the pleasure of talk tonight, since there are many labours to me.

08:05.160 --> 08:07.220
But you will sleep, I pray.

08:09.000 --> 08:14.500
I passed to my room and went to bed, and, strange to say, slept without dreaming.

08:15.860 --> 08:17.520
Despair has its own calms.

08:22.320 --> 08:26.460
This morning when I woke I thought I would provide myself with some papers and envelopes

08:26.460 --> 08:31.280
from my bag and keep them in my pocket, so that I might write in case I should get an opportunity.

08:32.060 --> 08:40.440
But again, a surprise. Again, a shock. Every scrap of paper was gone, and with it all my notes,

08:40.760 --> 08:45.620
my memoranda, relating to railways and travel, my letter of credit, in fact all that might be

08:45.620 --> 08:47.500
useful to me were I once outside the castle. I was in a hurry to go to bed, and I had been

08:47.500 --> 08:54.580
in the castle. I sat and pondered a while, and then some thought occurred to me, and I made

08:54.580 --> 09:00.840
search of my portmanteau and in the wardrobe where I had placed my clothes. The suit in which I had

09:00.840 --> 09:07.060
travelled was gone, and also my overcoat and rug. I could find no trace of them anywhere.

09:08.180 --> 09:11.020
This looked like some new scheme of villainy.

09:13.900 --> 09:14.980
17th of June

09:16.520 --> 09:22.400
This morning as I was sitting on the edge of my bed, cudgeling my brains, I heard without

09:22.400 --> 09:27.120
a crackling of whips and pounding and scraping of horses' feet up the rocky path beyond the

09:27.120 --> 09:33.700
courtyard. With joy I hurried to the window and saw drive into the yard two great lighter wagons,

09:34.060 --> 09:40.220
each drawn by eight sturdy horses, and at the head of each pair a Slovak, with his wide hat,

09:40.220 --> 09:47.020
great nail-studded belt, dirty sheepskin and high boots. They had also their long staves in hand.

09:48.240 --> 09:52.920
I ran to the door intending to descend and try to join them through the main hall,

09:53.320 --> 10:00.000
as I thought that way might be opened for them. Again a shock, my door was fastened on the outside.

10:02.240 --> 10:06.760
Then I ran to the window and cried to them. They looked up at me stupidly and pointed,

10:06.760 --> 10:12.160
but just then the hat man of the Tsigani came out and, seeing them pointing to my window,

10:12.480 --> 10:14.880
said something, at which they laughed.

10:17.080 --> 10:23.380
Henceforth no effort of mine, no piteous cry or agonized entreaty, would make them even look at

10:23.380 --> 10:30.240
me. They resolutely turned away. The lighter wagons contained great square boxes with handles of

10:30.240 --> 10:34.820
thick rope. These were evidently empty by the ease with which the Slovaks handled them,

10:34.820 --> 10:40.140
and by their resonance when they were roughly moved. When they were all unloaded and packed

10:40.140 --> 10:44.820
in a great heap in one corner of the yard, the Slovaks were given some money by the Tsigani,

10:45.380 --> 10:49.540
and, spitting on it for luck, lazily went each to his horse's head.

10:50.560 --> 10:54.340
Shortly afterwards I heard the crackling of their whips die away in the distance.

10:57.580 --> 11:03.440
24th of June. Last night the Count left me early and locked himself into his own room.

11:04.080 --> 11:08.720
As soon as I dared I ran up the winding stair and looked out of the window, which opened south.

11:09.460 --> 11:12.440
I thought I would watch for the Count, for there is something going on.

11:13.280 --> 11:17.400
The Tsigani are quartered somewhere in the castle and are doing work of some kind.

11:17.900 --> 11:24.120
I know it, for now and then I hear a far away muffled sound as of matic and spade,

11:24.400 --> 11:29.200
and whatever it is, it must be the end of some ruthless villainy.

11:29.740 --> 11:34.780
I had been at the window somewhat less than half an hour when I saw something coming out

11:34.780 --> 11:41.140
of the Count's window. I drew back and watched carefully, and saw the whole man emerge.

11:42.340 --> 11:47.360
It was a new shock to me to find that he had on the suit of clothes which I had worn whilst

11:47.360 --> 11:52.740
travelling here, and slung over his shoulder the terrible bag which I had seen the women take away.

11:53.560 --> 11:57.600
There could be no doubt as to his quest, and in my garb too.

11:58.380 --> 12:04.040
This then is his new scheme of evil, that he will allow others to see me as they think,

12:04.340 --> 12:08.200
so that he may both leave evidence that I have been seen in the towns or villages,

12:08.520 --> 12:14.040
posting my own letters, and that any wickedness which he may do shall by the local people be

12:14.040 --> 12:21.040
attributed to me. It makes me rage to think that this can go on, and whilst I am shut up here,

12:21.460 --> 12:27.580
a veritable prisoner, but without that protection of the law which is even a

12:28.260 --> 12:33.000
I thought I would watch for the Count's return, and for a long time sat doggedly at the window.

12:34.100 --> 12:38.000
Then I began to notice that there were some quaint little specks floating in the rays of

12:38.000 --> 12:44.220
the moonlight. They were like the tiniest grains of dust, and they whirled round and gathered in

12:44.220 --> 12:51.300
clusters in a nebulous sort of way. I watched them with a sense of soothing, and a sort of

12:51.300 --> 12:57.280
calm stole over me. I leaned back in the embrasure in a more comfortable position,

12:57.580 --> 13:00.740
so that I could enjoy more fully the aerial gambling.

13:03.420 --> 13:08.860
Something made me start up, a low, piteous howling of dogs somewhere far below in the valley,

13:09.380 --> 13:14.960
which was hidden from my sight. Louder it seemed to ring in my ears, and the floating motes of dust

13:14.960 --> 13:20.800
take new shapes to the sound as they danced in the moonlight. I felt myself struggling to awake to

13:20.800 --> 13:27.100
some call of my instincts. Nay, my very soul was struggling, and my half-remembered sensibilities

13:27.100 --> 13:34.840
were striving to answer the call. I was becoming hypnotized. Quicker and quicker danced the dust.

13:35.580 --> 13:39.500
The moonbeams seemed to quiver as they went by me into the mass of gloom beyond.

13:40.460 --> 13:43.660
More and more they gathered till they seemed to take dim phantom shapes.

13:44.300 --> 13:50.460
And then I started, broad awake, in full possession of my senses, and ran screaming from the place.

13:51.980 --> 13:56.360
The phantom shapes which were becoming gradually materialized from the moonbeams

13:56.360 --> 13:59.840
were those three ghostly women to whom I was doomed.

14:01.480 --> 14:05.260
I fled and felt somewhat safer in my own room where there was no moonlight

14:05.260 --> 14:07.320
and where the lamp was burning brightly.

14:09.600 --> 14:14.640
When a couple of hours had passed, I heard something stirring in the Count's room,

14:15.160 --> 14:23.080
something like a sharp wail quickly suppressed. And then there was silence, deep, awful silence,

14:23.080 --> 14:29.100
which chilled me. With a beating heart, I tried the door, but I was locked in my

14:29.100 --> 14:33.560
prison and could do nothing. I sat down and simply cried.

14:35.580 --> 14:40.440
As I sat, I heard a sound in the courtyard without, the agonized cry of a woman.

14:41.340 --> 14:44.820
I rushed to the window, and throwing it up, peered between the bars.

14:46.980 --> 14:51.240
There, indeed, was a woman with disheveled hair, holding her hands over her heart,

14:51.240 --> 14:56.260
as one distressed with running. She was leaning against the corner of the gateway.

14:57.440 --> 15:01.520
When she saw my face at the window, she threw herself forward and shouted in a voice

15:01.520 --> 15:07.920
laden with menace, Monster, give me my child. She threw herself on her knees,

15:08.280 --> 15:12.080
and raising up her hands, cried the same words in tones which rung my heart.

15:13.140 --> 15:17.360
Then she tore her hair and beat her breast and abandoned herself to all the violences

15:17.360 --> 15:23.220
of extravagant emotion. Finally she threw herself forward, and though I could not see her,

15:23.640 --> 15:26.540
I could hear the beating of her naked hands against the door.

15:28.160 --> 15:34.420
Somewhere high overhead, probably on the tower, I heard the voice of the count calling in his harsh

15:34.420 --> 15:40.820
metallic whisper. His call seemed to be answered from far and wide by the howling of wolves.

15:42.180 --> 15:47.120
Before many minutes had passed, a pack of them poured like a pent-up dam when liberated,

15:47.120 --> 15:53.080
through the wide entrance into the courtyard. There was no cry from the woman,

15:53.640 --> 16:00.920
and the howling of the wolves was but short. Before long they streamed away singly, licking their lips.

16:03.440 --> 16:10.000
I could not pity her, for I knew now what had become of her child, and she was better dead.

16:11.700 --> 16:20.520
What shall I do? What can I do? How can I escape from this dreadful thing of night, gloom, and fear?

16:23.440 --> 16:24.700
25th of June

16:26.320 --> 16:29.520
No man knows till he has suffered from the night

16:29.520 --> 16:33.360
how sweet and dear to his heart and eye the morning can be.

16:34.560 --> 16:39.240
When the sun grew so high this morning that it struck the top of the great gateway opposite my

16:39.240 --> 16:45.200
window, the high spot which it touched seemed to me as if the dove from the ark had lighted there.

16:46.400 --> 16:51.140
My fear fell from me as if it had been a vaporous garment which dissolved in the warmth.

16:52.720 --> 16:56.640
I must take action of some sort whilst the courage of the day is upon me.

16:57.020 --> 17:02.240
Last night one of my post-dated letters went to post, the first of that fatal series which is to

17:02.240 --> 17:08.740
blot out the very traces of my existence from the earth. Let me not think of it. Action.

17:10.140 --> 17:15.940
It has always been at night time that I've been molested or threatened or in some way in danger or in fear.

17:17.220 --> 17:22.860
I have not yet seen the count in the daylight. Can it be that he sleeps when others wake?

17:23.760 --> 17:29.200
That he may be awake whilst they sleep? If I could only get into his room.

17:30.380 --> 17:35.280
But there is no possible way. The door is always locked. No way for me.

17:36.920 --> 17:46.440
Yes, there is a way, if one dares to take it. Where his body has gone, why may not another body go?

17:47.420 --> 17:53.560
I have seen him myself crawl from his window. Why should not I imitate him and go in by his window?

17:55.160 --> 17:58.900
The chances are desperate, but my need is more desperate still.

17:59.540 --> 18:05.700
I shall risk it. At the worst, it can only be death. And a man's death is not a calf's.

18:06.500 --> 18:11.700
And the dreaded hereafter may still be open to me. God help me in my task.

18:13.180 --> 18:18.060
Goodbye, Mina, if I fail. Goodbye, my faithful friend and second father.

18:19.240 --> 18:23.200
Goodbye, all, and last of all, Mina.

18:25.640 --> 18:33.220
Same day, later. I have made the effort, and, God helping me, have come safely back to this room.

18:33.960 --> 18:45.380
I must put down every detail in order. I went whilst my courage was fresh, straight to the window on the south side, and at once got outside on this side.

18:46.140 --> 18:51.280
The stones are big and roughly cut, and the mortar has by process of time been washed away between them.

18:52.060 --> 18:55.440
I took off my boots and ventured out on the desperate way.

18:57.060 --> 19:06.500
I looked down once, so as to make sure that a sudden glimpse of the awful depth would not overcome me, but after that kept my eyes away from it.

19:07.380 --> 19:16.300
I know pretty well the direction and distance of the Count's window, and made for it as well as I could, having regard to the opportunities available.

19:17.080 --> 19:27.680
I did not feel dizzy, I suppose I was too excited, and the time seemed ridiculously short, till I found myself standing on the windowsill and trying to raise up the sash.

19:28.880 --> 19:33.920
I was filled with agitation, however, when I bent down and slid feet foremost in through the window.

19:34.760 --> 19:40.020
Then I looked around for the Count, but with surprise and gladness made a discovery.

19:41.020 --> 19:47.860
The room was empty. It was barely furnished with odd things which seemed to have never been used.

19:49.920 --> 19:54.320
The furniture was something the same style as that in the south rooms, and was covered with dust.

19:55.360 --> 19:59.260
I looked for the key, but it was not in the lock, and I could not find it anywhere.

20:00.580 --> 20:05.460
The only thing I found was a great heap of gold in one corner, gold of all kinds.

20:06.020 --> 20:14.140
Roman, and British, and Austrian, and Hungarian, and Greek, and Turkish money, covered with a film of dust as though it had lain long on the ground.

20:15.340 --> 20:18.320
None of it that I noticed was less than 300 years old.

20:19.240 --> 20:24.260
There were also chains and ornaments, some jeweled, but all of them old and stained.

20:25.780 --> 20:27.800
At one corner of the room was a heavy door.

20:28.420 --> 20:34.600
I tried it, for since I could not find the key of the room or the key of the outer door, which was the main object of my search,

20:34.600 --> 20:39.620
I must make further examination, or all my efforts would be in vain.

20:40.720 --> 20:46.660
It was open, and led through a stone passage to a circular stairway which went steeply down.

20:48.100 --> 20:55.140
I descended, minding carefully where I went, for the stairs were dark, being only lit by loopholes in the heavy masonry.

20:56.140 --> 21:01.280
At the bottom there was a dark, tunnel-like passage through which came a deathly,

21:01.280 --> 21:05.120
sickly odor, the odor of old earth newly turned.

21:06.420 --> 21:09.540
As I went through the passage the smell grew closer and heavier.

21:11.260 --> 21:19.780
At last I pulled open a heavy door which stood ajar, and found myself in an old ruined chapel, which had evidently been used as a graveyard.

21:21.300 --> 21:25.360
The roof was broken, and in two places were steps leading to vaults,

21:25.360 --> 21:29.700
but the ground had recently been dug over, and the earth placed in great wooden boxes.

21:30.540 --> 21:33.420
Manifestly those which had been brought by the Slovaks.

21:34.800 --> 21:39.900
There was nobody about, and I made a search over every inch of the ground so as not to lose a chance.

21:40.960 --> 21:47.200
I went down even into the vaults, where the dim light struggled, although to do so was a dread to my very soul.

21:48.600 --> 21:54.260
Into two of these I went, but saw nothing except fragments of old coffins and piles of dust.

21:55.220 --> 21:58.220
In the third, however, I made a discovery.

21:59.880 --> 22:08.000
There, in one of the great boxes, of which there were fifty in all, on a pile of newly dug earth, lay the Count.

22:09.020 --> 22:10.920
He was either dead or asleep.

22:11.680 --> 22:17.880
I could not say which, for eyes were open and stony, but without the glassiness of death,

22:18.480 --> 22:21.860
and the cheeks had the warmth of life through all their pallor.

22:22.660 --> 22:24.700
The lips were as red as ever,

22:25.360 --> 22:29.320
but there was no sign of movement, no pulse, no breath.

22:29.780 --> 22:31.240
No beating of the heart.

22:32.800 --> 22:35.980
I bent over him and tried to find any sign of life, but in vain.

22:37.200 --> 22:41.480
He could not have lain there long, for the earthy smell would have passed away in a few hours.

22:42.640 --> 22:46.660
By the side of the box was its cover, pierced with holes here and there.

22:47.920 --> 22:52.340
I thought he might have the keys on him, but when I went to search I saw the dead eyes,

22:52.800 --> 22:55.000
and in them dead, though they were,

22:55.700 --> 22:57.120
such look of hate.

22:57.820 --> 23:03.820
Though unconscious of me or my presence, that I fled from the place, and leaving the Count's room by the window,

23:04.500 --> 23:06.160
crawled again up the castle wall.

23:07.400 --> 23:11.100
Regaining my room, I threw myself panting upon the bed and tried to think.

23:14.080 --> 23:15.040
29th of June.

23:16.440 --> 23:20.920
Today is the date of my last letter, and the Count has taken steps to prove that it was genuine,

23:21.200 --> 23:25.040
for again I saw him leave the castle by the same window and in my clothes.

23:25.760 --> 23:32.880
As he went down the wall, lizard fashion, I wished I had a gun or some lethal weapon that I might destroy him.

23:34.200 --> 23:39.500
But I fear that no weapon wrought along by man's hand would have any effect upon him.

23:40.500 --> 23:44.440
I dared not wait to see him return, for I feared to see those weird sisters.

23:45.380 --> 23:49.420
I came back to the library and read there till I fell asleep.

23:51.660 --> 23:53.420
I was awakened by the Count,

23:54.140 --> 23:57.620
who looked at me as grimly as a man could look, as he said,

23:58.880 --> 24:01.820
Tomorrow, my friend, we must part.

24:03.040 --> 24:05.400
You return to your beautiful England,

24:06.140 --> 24:10.220
eye to some work which may have such an end that we may never meet.

24:11.320 --> 24:13.580
Your letter home has been dispatched.

24:14.420 --> 24:16.340
Tomorrow I shall not be here,

24:16.700 --> 24:18.900
but all shall be ready for your journey.

24:19.720 --> 24:24.140
In the morning come the Sagani, who have some labors of their own here,

24:24.420 --> 24:26.760
and also come some Slovaks.

24:27.420 --> 24:30.620
When they have gone, my carriage shall come for you,

24:30.760 --> 24:32.900
and shall bear you to the Borgo Pass

24:32.900 --> 24:36.340
to meet the diligence from Bokovena to Bistritz.

24:37.700 --> 24:41.760
But I am in hopes that I shall see more of you at Castle Dracula.

24:43.220 --> 24:46.760
I suspected him and determined to test his sincerity.

24:48.420 --> 24:52.520
Sincerity seems like a profanation of the word to write it in connection with such a monster,

24:52.560 --> 24:53.960
so I asked him point-blank.

24:55.340 --> 24:56.860
Why may I not go tonight?

24:58.500 --> 25:02.820
Because, dear sir, my coachmen and horses are away on a mission.

25:04.080 --> 25:07.220
But I would walk with pleasure. I want to get away at once.

25:08.440 --> 25:11.840
He smiled such a soft, smooth diabolical smile

25:11.840 --> 25:14.940
that I knew there was some trick behind his smoothness.

25:15.580 --> 25:16.280
He said,

25:17.020 --> 25:18.040
And your baggage?

25:18.920 --> 25:22.160
I do not care about it. I can send for it some other time.

25:23.400 --> 25:28.880
The Count stood up and said, with a sweet courtesy which made me rub my eyes, it seems so real,

25:30.340 --> 25:34.040
You English have a saying which is close to my heart,

25:34.440 --> 25:36.900
for its spirit is that which rules our boyars.

25:37.920 --> 25:41.040
Welcome the coming. Speed the parting guest.

25:42.720 --> 25:44.340
Come with me, my dear young friend.

25:44.340 --> 25:47.680
Not an hour shall you wait in my house against your will,

25:48.140 --> 25:51.960
though sad am I at your going, and that you so suddenly desire it.

25:52.640 --> 25:53.040
Come.

25:54.380 --> 25:58.940
With a stately gravity he, with the lamp, proceeded me down the stairs and along the hall.

26:00.200 --> 26:01.220
Suddenly he stopped.

26:02.280 --> 26:02.660
Hark!

26:04.760 --> 26:07.120
Close at hand came the howling of many wolves.

26:07.720 --> 26:10.900
It was almost as if the sounds sprang up at the rising of his hand,

26:10.900 --> 26:14.860
just as the music of a great orchestra seems to leap under the baton of the conductor.

26:16.300 --> 26:20.760
After a pause of a moment he proceeded in his stately way to the door,

26:21.340 --> 26:26.400
drew back the ponderous bolts, unhooked the heavy chains, and began to draw it open.

26:27.920 --> 26:31.260
To my intense astonishment I saw that it was unlocked.

26:32.580 --> 26:36.380
Suspiciously I looked all around, but could see no key of any kind.

26:37.960 --> 26:43.080
As the door began to open, the howling of the wolves without grew louder and angrier.

26:43.640 --> 26:48.280
Their red jaws with champing teeth, and their blunt clawed feet as they leaped,

26:48.600 --> 26:50.020
came in through the opening door.

26:51.020 --> 26:54.300
I knew then that to struggle at the moment against the Count was useless.

26:54.820 --> 26:58.080
With such allies as these at his command, I could do nothing.

26:58.880 --> 27:03.320
But still the door continued slowly to open, and only the Count's body stood in a gap.

27:04.460 --> 27:07.640
Suddenly it struck me that this might be the moment and means of my doom.

27:08.280 --> 27:11.800
I was to be given to the wolves, and at my own instigation.

27:13.280 --> 27:16.500
There was a diabolical wickedness in the idea great enough for the Count,

27:17.300 --> 27:18.860
and as the last chance I cried out,

27:19.620 --> 27:21.760
Shut the door! I shall wait till morning!

27:22.780 --> 27:26.580
And I covered my face with my hands to hide my tears of bitter disappointment.

27:28.460 --> 27:32.020
With one sweep of his powerful arm, the Count threw the door shut,

27:32.020 --> 27:36.740
and the great bolts clanged and echoed through the hall as they shot back into their places.

27:38.600 --> 27:42.840
In silence we returned to the library, and after a minute or two I went to my own room.

27:44.320 --> 27:48.860
The last I saw of Count Dracula was his kissing his hand to me,

27:49.180 --> 27:55.300
with a red light of triumph in his eyes, and with a smile that Judas in hell might be proud of.

27:57.220 --> 28:01.840
When I was in my room and about to lie down, I thought I heard a whispering at my door.

28:02.980 --> 28:09.320
I went to it softly and listened. Unless my ears deceived me, I heard the voice of the Count.

28:10.720 --> 28:16.780
Back, back to your own place. Your time has not yet come.

28:18.320 --> 28:24.820
Wait, have patience. Tonight is mine. Tomorrow night is yours.

28:26.320 --> 28:30.180
There was a low sweet ripple of laughter, and in a rage I threw open the door,

28:30.180 --> 28:33.760
and saw without the three terrible women licking their lips.

28:34.900 --> 28:38.360
As I appeared, they all joined in a horrible laugh and ran away.

28:39.900 --> 28:46.260
I came back to my room and threw myself on my knees. It is then so near the end.

28:48.520 --> 28:53.120
Tomorrow, tomorrow. Lord, help me and those to whom I am dear.

28:55.320 --> 29:03.080
30th of June. These may be the last words I ever write in this diary. I slept till just before the

29:03.080 --> 29:08.780
dawn, and when I woke, threw myself on my knees, for I determined that if death came, he should

29:08.780 --> 29:16.060
find me ready. At last I felt that subtle change in the air, and knew that the morning had come.

29:17.380 --> 29:21.060
Then came the welcome cock crow, and I felt that I was safe.

29:22.220 --> 29:28.580
With a glad heart, I opened the door and ran down the hall. I had seen that the door was unlocked,

29:29.100 --> 29:34.860
and now escape was before me. With hands that trembled with eagerness, I unhooked the chains

29:34.860 --> 29:42.360
and threw back the massive bolts. But the door would not move. Despair seized me. I pulled and

29:42.360 --> 29:51.040
pulled at the door, and shook it till, massive as it was, it rattled in its casement. I could see the

29:51.040 --> 29:58.140
count. Then a wild desire took me to obtain the key at any risk, and I determined then and there

29:58.140 --> 30:04.940
to scale the wall again and gain the count's room. He might kill me, but death now seemed the happier

30:04.940 --> 30:11.140
choice of evils. Without a pause, I rushed up to the east window and scrambled down the wall as

30:11.140 --> 30:18.280
before, into the count's room. It was empty, but that was as I expected. I could not see a key

30:18.280 --> 30:23.440
anywhere but the heap of gold remained. I went through the door in the corner and down the

30:23.440 --> 30:29.660
winding stair and along the dark passage to the old chapel. I knew now well enough where to find

30:29.660 --> 30:37.080
the monster I sought. The great box was in the same place, close against the wall, but the lid

30:37.080 --> 30:42.420
was laid on it, not fastened down, but with the nails ready in their places to be hammered home.

30:43.880 --> 30:49.400
I knew I must reach the body for the key, so I raised the lid and laid it back against the wall,

30:49.980 --> 30:56.140
and then I saw something which filled my very soul with horror. There lay the count,

30:57.020 --> 31:03.380
but looking as if his youth had been half restored, for the white hair and mustache were changed to

31:03.380 --> 31:11.100
dark iron gray, the cheeks were fuller, and the white skin seemed ruby red underneath. The mouth

31:11.100 --> 31:16.040
was redder than ever, for on the lips were gouts of fresh blood which trickled from the corners of

31:16.040 --> 31:21.920
the mouth and ran down over the chin and neck. Even the deep burning eyes seemed set amongst

31:21.920 --> 31:27.040
swollen flesh, for the lids and pouches underneath were bloated. It seemed as if the whole awful

31:27.040 --> 31:34.620
creature was simply gorged with blood. He lay like a filthy leech, exhausted with his repletion.

31:36.160 --> 31:40.940
I shuddered as I bent over to touch him, and every sense in me revolted at the contact,

31:41.540 --> 31:48.360
but I had to search, or I was lost. The coming night might see my own body a banquet in a

31:48.360 --> 31:55.700
similar war to those horrid three. I felt all over the body, but no sign could I find of the key.

31:57.060 --> 31:59.620
Then I stopped and looked at the count.

32:01.160 --> 32:07.620
There was a mocking smile on the bloated face which seemed to drive me mad. This was the being

32:07.620 --> 32:13.540
I was helping to transfer to London, where perhaps for centuries to come he might, amongst his

32:13.540 --> 32:19.440
teeming millions, satiate his lust for blood and create a new and ever-widening circle of semi-demons

32:19.440 --> 32:29.600
to batten on the helpless. The very thought drove me mad. A terrible desire came upon me to rid the

32:29.600 --> 32:35.360
shovel which the workmen had been using to fill the cases, and lifting it high, struck with the

32:35.360 --> 32:42.280
edge downward at the hateful face. But as I did so, the head turned and the eyes fell upon me with

32:42.280 --> 32:48.360
all their blaze of basilisk horror. The sight seemed to paralyze me, and the shovel turned in

32:48.360 --> 32:55.080
my hand and glanced from my face, merely making a deep gash above the forehead. The shovel fell

32:55.080 --> 32:59.580
from my hand across the box, and as I pulled it away, the flange of the blade caught the edge of

32:59.580 --> 33:06.140
the lid which fell over again and hid the horrid thing from my sight. The last glimpse I had was

33:06.140 --> 33:12.500
of the bloated face, blood-stained and fixed with a grin of malice which would have held its own in

33:12.500 --> 33:19.920
the nethermost hell. I thought and thought what should be my next move, but my brain seemed on

33:19.920 --> 33:28.380
fire, and I waited with a despairing feeling growing over me. As I waited, I heard in the

33:28.940 --> 33:32.240
through their song the rolling of heavy wheels and the cracking of whips.

33:33.660 --> 33:36.700
The sigarni and the slovaks of whom the Count had spoken were coming.

33:37.880 --> 33:42.380
With a last look around and at the box which contained the vile body, I ran from the place

33:42.380 --> 33:46.060
and gained the Count's room determined to rush out at the moment the door should be opened.

33:47.160 --> 33:52.100
With strained ears, I listened and heard downstairs the grinding of the key in the great lock

33:52.100 --> 33:57.720
and the falling back of the heavy door. There must have been some other means of entry,

33:57.720 --> 34:03.820
or someone had a key for one of the locked doors. Then there came the sound of many feet

34:03.820 --> 34:10.860
tramping and dying away in some passage which sent up a clanging echo. I turned to run down again

34:10.860 --> 34:15.540
towards the vault where I might find the new entrance, but at the moment there seemed to come

34:15.540 --> 34:20.760
a violent puff of wind and the door to the winding stair blew too with a shock that set the dust from

34:20.760 --> 34:26.140
the lintels flying. When I ran to push it open, I found that it was hopelessly fast.

34:26.720 --> 34:31.960
I was again a prisoner and the net of doom was closing around me more closely.

34:33.900 --> 34:38.760
As I write, there is in the passage below a sound of many tramping feet and the crash of

34:38.760 --> 34:43.280
weights being set down heavily, doubtless the boxes with their freight of earth.

34:44.380 --> 34:48.380
There was a sound of hammering. It is the box being nailed down.

34:49.520 --> 34:54.920
Now I can hear the heavy feet tramping again along the hall with many other idle feet coming

34:54.920 --> 35:02.220
behind them. The door is shut. The chains rattle. There is a grinding of the key in the lock.

35:03.360 --> 35:07.240
I can hear the key withdrawn, then another door opens and shuts.

35:08.060 --> 35:14.420
I hear the creaking of lock and bolt. Hark! In the courtyard and down the rocky way,

35:14.500 --> 35:19.280
the roll of heavy wheels, the crack of whips, and the chorus of the sagani as they pass into the

35:19.280 --> 35:25.840
distance. I am alone in the castle with those horrible women.

35:28.340 --> 35:32.840
Mina is a woman and there is not in common. They are devils of the pit.

35:34.420 --> 35:39.020
I shall not remain alone with them. I shall try to scale the castle wall farther than I have

35:39.020 --> 35:44.140
yet attempted. I shall take some of the gold with me lest I want it later. I may find a way from

35:44.140 --> 35:49.460
this dreadful place. And then a way for home. A way to the quickest and nearest train,

35:49.760 --> 35:54.720
away from the cursed spot, from this cursed land where the devil and his children still walk with

35:54.720 --> 36:00.700
earthly feet. At least God's mercy is better than that of those monsters and the precipice

36:00.700 --> 36:08.960
is steep and high. At its foot a man may sleep as a man. Goodbye all. Mina.

36:12.120 --> 36:13.780
End of chapter 4

